Natural selection seems to have overshot the mark just a little bit, but, as I predicted, last summer I began to see a few <a href="http://pandasthumb.org/archives/2007/04/dandelions-acqu.html">green dandelions</a> in my lawn.

<figure alt="IMG_0279_GreenDLion_600.png" src="http://pandasthumb.org/archives/2011/03/30/IMG_0279_GreenDLion_600.png" width="600" height="557">
<big><i>Taraxacum officinale viride</i> -- green <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taraxacum">dandelion</a>.</big> The visitor is a longhorn beetle, <a href="http://bugguide.net/node/view/140344"><i>Crossidius</i> sp.</a>, according to <a href="http://bugeric.blogspot.com">Eric Eaton</a>, author, <i>Kaufman Field Guide to Insects of North America</i>.
